    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-03-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-03-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="423"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d423">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 033.1100 K77/86.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">American Minister</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-09">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 9, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The party of the Secretary of State consists of himself and Mrs. Knox, Mr. and
                    Mrs. Hugh S. Knox, Mr. and Mrs. P. C. Knox, Jr., <pb facs="0414" n="298"
                        xml:id="pg_298"/> one valet, one maid, Mr. Coombs and Mr. Doyle of the
                    Department; Mr. Heinl of Leslie’s Weekly, Mr. Harmon of New York Sun, Mr. Hale
                    of World’s Work, Mr. McKernon of Associated Press, Mr. Vargas of International
                    News Association, one military aide, one naval aide, one servant. The party
                    expect to arrive April 10.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
